{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}
{{more citations needed|date=March 2013}}

[[Image:edinburgh fringe festival.jpg|thumb|[[Edinburgh Festival Fringe|Edinburgh Fringe]], [[Scotland]], a notable arts festival]]
An '''arts festival''' is a [[festival]] that can encompass a wide range of art genres including music, dance, film, fine art, literature, poetry etc. and isn't solely focused on "visual arts." Arts festivals may feature a mixed program that include music, literature, comedy, children's entertainment, science, or street theatre, and are typically presented in venues over a period of time ranging from as short as a day or a weekend to a month.<ref name="KorzaMagie1989">{{cite book|author1=Pam Korza|author2=Dian Magie|title=The Arts Festival Work Kit|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uOrR9uPZ-IgC|year=1989|publisher=Arts Extension Service|isbn=978-0-945464-02-0}}</ref> Each event within the program is usually separately ticketed.

Arts festivals are largely curated by an artistic director who handles the organizations' artistic direction and can encompass different genres, including [[fringe festivals|fringe theater festivals]] that are open access, making arts festivals distinctive from greenfield festivals, which typically are weekend camping festivals such as [[Glastonbury Festival|Glastonbury]], and Visual Arts Festivals, which concentrate on the visual arts.

Another type of arts festivals are music festivals, which are outdoor musical events usually spanning a weekend, featuring a number of bands and musical genres including pop, rock, heavy-metal, and more. Since the 1960s, world-music festivals have become popular in a variety of countries. The most well-recognized music festival was [[Woodstock]], which took place in 1969 in Bethel, New York. It was attended by 400,000 people and featured performances by The Who, Jimi Hendrix, Janis Joplin, and the Grateful Dead.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Hutchinson Unabridged Encyclopedia with Atlas and Weather Guide|last=|first=|publisher=Helikon|year=2016|isbn=|edition=1|location=Abington UK|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=40 years after Woodstock, a more harmonious society|last=14 August 2009|first=|date=|work=USA TODAY|access-date=5 November 2017|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref>

==History==
Probably the two oldest arts festivals are located in England. The [[Three Choirs Festival]] in the West of England was established as a "yearly musical assembly" by 1719.<ref>[http://www.3choirs.org/about/three-choirs-history-festival-anthony-boden.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091215092316/http://www.3choirs.org/about/three-choirs-history-festival-anthony-boden.html |date=15 December 2009 }}</ref> The other is the [[Norfolk and Norwich Festival]] which first took place in 1772.<ref>[http://www.norwich.gov.uk/internet_docs/docs/Unitary_Council/AnnexB.pdf ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070621211721/http://www.norwich.gov.uk/internet_docs/docs/Unitary_Council/AnnexB.pdf |date=21 June 2007 }}</ref> The largest arts festival in England today is the [[Brighton Festival Fringe]].

Leading arts festivals include the [[Edinburgh Festival]] in [[Edinburgh]], [[Adelaide Festival of Arts]] in [[Adelaide]], the [[Biennale of Sydney]], [[Festival d'Avignon]] in [[Avignon]], France,<ref>{{cite conference |first=Robyn |last=Archer |authorlink=Robyn Archer |title=Putting Festivals in their Place |booktitle=Keynote address to the British Festivals Association conference |date=October 2006 |location=Cardiff }}</ref> and [[TIMF|Tongyeong International Music Festival]] in [[Tongyeong]], Korea and Sanskruti Arts Festival, Upvan, India. One-off arts festivals have included the Liverpool08 [[European Capital of Culture]] in 2008.

In the summer of 1793, revolutionary France was invaded by foreign armies which resulted in the destruction of all signs of royalty. During this time, French citizens sang, danced, and theaters as well as indoor music multiplied. By 1793, two dozen new venues for music and drama had been established, as a result of the end of restrictive monopolies that previously ruled. Art dealings were rapidly increasing and as a flood of paintings were for sale, this reduced artists to near impoverishment. Therefore, as a result, this called for an attempt to replace the old system of the arts with a new one. This gave rise to festivals that were used not only as an artistic outlet, but also for political protest against the old government system. These festivals often included religious symbolism, political messages and embodied the spirit of liberty, equality and fraternity. In 1792, The "Festival of Liberty" included a Declaration of the rights of man, busts of Voltaire, Rousseau, and Franklin, a hymn to liberty, women in white carrying chains, and a large chariot with a seated statue of liberty <ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/45304719|title=The invention of art : a cultural history|last=1934-|first=Shiner, L. E. (Larry E.),|date=2001|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=0226753425|location=Chicago|oclc=45304719}}</ref>

==Types of arts festivals==
{{See also|:Category:Arts festivals by type}}

===Arts festival===
{{Main|:Category:Arts festivals}}
An Arts Festival is an umbrella-term for a festival that focuses on multiple art genres including fine art (painting, drawing, pottery), music, photography, film, and other visual styles <ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wisegeek.net/what-is-an-art-festival.htm|title=What Is an Art Festival? (with pictures)|work=wiseGEEK|access-date=7 November 2017}}</ref> [[Fringe festival]]s are a type of arts festival, often focusing on many arts but sometimes focusing on a specific art such as theater more than others.<ref name="KorzaMagie1989"/> Some subgenres of an arts festival include art fairs, theater festivals, dance festivals, film festivals, music festivals (pop festivals) and more. {{Main|:Category:Art festivals|:Category:Art fairs}}

===Art Fair===
An '''art fair''' is a subgenre of arts festival that focuses on [[visual art]] specifically, or specific fields of visual art such as [[List of new media art festivals|new media art festivals]]. Other subgenres of art festivals are termed [[:Category:Photography festivals|photography festivals]] or [[:Category:Street art festivals|street art festivals]], for example. Typically, an art fair has a wide range of artists, art dealers, collectors, and curators who buy or sell artwork in a venue, or gallery, that is open to the public. Some items for sale include photography, paintings, drawings, metalwork, handcrafted items and pottery.

Festivals of visual arts are also not to be confused with '''commercial art fairs'''. Artists participate in the most important of such festival exhibitions by invitation, and these exhibitions (e.g. the [[Venice Biennale]]) are organised by internationally recognized curators chosen by a committee of peers. Conversely art fairs are market-oriented shows where art dealers exhibit and sell the work of the artists they represent.

===Theater festival===
{{expand section|date=December 2015}}
{{Main|:Category:Dance festivals}}The first drama festival was in 543BC, at the Athenian Great Dionysia. At the drama festivals, playwrights and poets competed to have their plays performed, and the actors competed to win the title for best performance. The performances were given in semi-circular auditorium cut into hillsides and capable of seating 10,000–20,000 people. The stage consisted of a dancing floor, an orchestra, dressing room and scene-building area, known as a skene. The actors were typically men who wore masks appropriate to the characters they represented, and each might play several parts.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/46471972|title=Chambers dictionary of world history|date=2000|publisher=Chambers|others=Lenman, Bruce., Anderson, Trevor.|isbn=0550130004|location=Edinburgh|oclc=46471972}}</ref>

===Film festival===
{{Main|:Category:Theatre festivals}}
{{expand section|date=December 2015}}
[[Film festival]]s are organized events, usually staged by universities, private organizations, local governments, or arts associations, that show films in cinemas or screening venues and provide filmmakers a chance to get notable recognition among fellow film enthusiasts. Films can include international and domestic releases and can even be on a specific film-maker, genre or subject matter. Film festivals are typically annual events and can feature full-length or short films.

One of the most notable Film Festivals is the [[Sundance Film Festival]], which originated from [[Salt Lake City]] in 1984 as part of the Sundance Institute organization and was founded by Robert Redford. To this date, it is one of the largest independent cinema festivals in the United States.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Sundance Film Festival|last=Myers|first=Alice|publisher=Salem Press Encyclopedia|year=2016|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>

===Poetry festival===
Poetry festivals are organized events staged by poetry and literature groups, local arts associations, private organizations and others that showcase contemporary poetry and provide a chance for poets to meet each other, celebrate poetry, critique each other's work and debate poetic issues. Poets can include international, national and local writers, and can include a specific theme. They are often held in a particular location over set dates. In contrast to literary festivals, poetry festivals put poetry centre stage. Poetry Festivals are typically annual events. Festivals established for more than 10 years in the UK include the festivals at Aldeburgh,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aldeburghpoetryfestival.org/|title=Aldeburgh Poetry Festival-You Will Enjoy Poetry In Its Entire Forms|author=|date=|website=Aldeburgh Poetry Festival}}</ref> Ledbury<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.poetry-festival.co.uk/|title=Ledbury Poetry Festival 29th June to 8th July 2018|website=Ledbury Poetry Festival}}</ref> and Torbay,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torbaypoetryfestival.co.uk/|title=Torbay Festival of Poetry|author=|date=|website=www.torbaypoetryfestival.co.uk}}</ref> and the Stanza Poetry festival in Scotland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stanzapoetry.org/festival|title=StAnza Festival 2018|website=StAnza, Scotland's Poetry Festival}}</ref> In India, a number of popular poetry festivals and in Northeast India, Guwahati Grand Poetry festival and Assam Arts Biennale, which began in 2018, are the first of its kind in the region.

