Following the [[1926 Lithuanian coup d'état]], Lithuania was led by what was known as the "Smetona regime," named after the leader of the coup, [[Antanas Smetona]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Lithuanian Soviet Socialist Republic|date=1968|publisher=Novosti Press Agency Publishing House|page=13|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tMoQAQAAIAAJ&dq=editions%3ALCCN76868068&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=formed}}</ref>  It was only in Soviet hands just under a year when German forces captured the Lithuanian SSR, and incorporated it into the [[Reichskommissariat Ostland]].  The Soviets retook the LSSR during the [[Baltic Operation]].  The LSSR gained its independence before any of the other Baltic states taken over by Russia, with the [[Act of the Re-Establishment of the State of Lithuania]] in 1990, though the Soviet Union refused to recognize its independence until 6 September 1991.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kiaupa|first=Zigmantas|title=The History of Lithuania|date=2005|publisher=Baltų lankų leid.|isbn=|page=322|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=psciAQAAIAAJ&dq=history+of+lithuania&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=independence}}</ref>
