|The [[Ili Kazakh Autonomous Prefecture|Ili]], [[Tacheng Prefecture|Tarbagatay]], and [[Altay Prefecture|Altay]] districts of [[Nationalist Government (China)|China]]
|In 1944, the Soviet-backed [[Ili Rebellion]] helped rebel forces take control of the area.<ref>{{cite book|last=Han|first=Enze|title=Contestation and Adaptation: The Politics of National Identity in China|date=2013|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0199936293|page=42|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QNxj74Zdxw0C&pg=PA42&dq=Second+East+Turkestan+Republic+-%22wikipedia%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=qQ51U_SiFPOtsAT5kIDoAg&ved=0CDwQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>  In the [[Sino-Soviet Treaty of Friendship and Alliance]], the Soviet Union agreed that it would no longer  support the ETR, in return for China letting the Soviet Union keep the [[Mongolian People's Republic]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Clarke|first=Michael E.|title=Xinjiang and China's Rise in Central Asia - A History|date=2011|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=1136827064|page=37|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jRhHphtBg-QC&pg=PA37&lpg=PA37&dq=second+east+turkestan+republic+declaration+of+independence&source=bl&ots=uvMl19-w0y&sig=Q__k1uSeLWdd5vZ5ss3LMP1R2o4&hl=en&sa=X&ei=lhJ1U5_4IYHJsQSr-IDYCQ&ved=0CGIQ6AEwBg#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>  In 1949, several of the ETR's leaders died in a plane crash while on their way to the [[Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference]].  China, who had been eyeing the area since its 1944 rebellion, seized the moment and took control of the area, where most of the remaining leadership accepted the area's [[Incorporation of Xinjiang into the People's Republic of China|incorporation into China]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Starr|first=S. Frederick|title=Xinjiang: China's Muslim Borderland|date=2004|publisher=M.E. Sharpe|isbn=076563192X|page=307|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GXj4a3gss8wC&q=plane+crash#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>
