|[[File:State Flag of Iran (1964-1980).svg|150px]]
|Southern [[Pahlavi dynasty|Iran]]
|Though Iran was invaded by Great Britain and the Soviet Union, neither of the countries had any immediate interests in Iran.  The reasons they invaded were simple; keep the Germans out, maintain the flow of oil, and assist the Soviets with transportation across the [[Trans-Iranian Railway]].  Because of this, British control over Iran was fairly light, save [[internal security]].  After the invasion, [[Rezā Shāh]] was dethroned, and his son, [[Mohammad Reza Pahlavi]] was put on the throne.<ref name=iran>{{cite book|title=The Cambridge History of Iran|date=1991|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=0521200954|pages=244–248|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H20Xt157iYUC&printsec=frontcover&dq=history+of+iran&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ng55U-SgDevQsQSV94G4Bw&sqi=2&ved=0CFMQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q&f=false|editor1=William Bayne Fisher |editor2=P. Avery |editor3=G. R. G. Hambly |editor4=C. Melville |accessdate=18 May 2014}}</ref>  After the Soviet's northern Iran became the [[Azerbaijan People's Government]], there became increasing civil unrest in the country.  In 1953, [[Mohammad Mosaddegh]], the democratically elected prime minister, was overthrown by the United States and Britain in the [[1953 Iranian coup d'état]], also known as the 28 Mordad coup.  The Shah was reinstated two days later.<ref>{{cite book|last=Abrahamian|first=Ervand|title=The Coup: 1953, the CIA, and the Roots of Modern U.S.-Iranian Relations|date=2013|publisher=The New Press|isbn=1595588264|page=xiv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l05NAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=iranian+coup&hl=en&sa=X&ei=jjV5U-3dNqnksATM8IKICA&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>
