|bgcolor=lightgreen|[[File:Flag of Manchukuo.svg|150px]]
|bgcolor=lightgreen|[[Manchuria]], [[Nationalist Government (China)|China]]
|bgcolor=lightgreen|Manchuria had long been a location of unrest, and the [[Mukden Incident]] was the perfect excuse for a Japanese occupation.  The Mukden Incident, in essence, was when the [[Kwantung Army]] set off a bomb along the [[South Manchuria Railway]], and used the explosion as an excuse to occupy Manchuria, blaming Chinese forces.<ref>{{cite book|last=Duara|first=Prasenjit|title=Sovereignty and Authenticity: Manchukuo and the East Asian Modern|date=2004|publisher=Rowman and Littlefield|isbn=0742530914|page=51|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L77chgc58X8C&printsec=frontcover&dq=manchukuo&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Y1R6U_PmH_OtsATfvoC4Cw&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>  Manchukuo was created in March 1932.  Despite the Japanese control of the area, they couldn't annex Manchuria into Japan due to their signing of the [[Nine-Power Treaty]].  After creating Manchukuo, Japan and Manchukuo signed several treaties allowing Japan to mobilize Manchuria's people and resources as it liked.<ref name=manchukuo>{{cite book|title=The State of Sovereignty: Territories, Laws, Populations|date=2009|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=0253220165|page=75|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c9aFgCO4Is0C&pg=PA75&dq=manchukuo&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Y1R6U_PmH_OtsATfvoC4Cw&ved=0CFkQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q&f=false|edition=illustrated|editor=Douglas Howland, Luise White}}</ref>  It was disestablished after the [[Soviet invasion of Manchuria]].<ref name=manchukuo /> {{rp|90}}
