|bgcolor=lightgreen|The East Hebei Autonomous Council, also sometimes called the East Ji Autonomous Council or the East Hopei Autonomous Anti-Communist Council, was headed by Yin Rugeng in 1935 to help protect economic interests in north China.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Minoru|first1=Kitamura|last2=Si-Yun|first2=Lin|title=The Reluctant Combatant: Japan and the Second Sino-Japanese War|date=2015|publisher=University Press of America|isbn=0761863257|page=15|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=https://books.google.com/books?id=QuBhAwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=15 Jul 2015}}</ref>  East Hebei protected Japan's economic interests by prohibiting the export of silver and the circulation of the notes of the Central Bank of China. They also set up their own Central Bank and began to issue notes which were supported by several banks, and were widely circulated in Tientsin, against the orders of the Chinese central government.  Following Japan's control of East Hebei, the region broke into reported "lawlessness," with the puppet state purportedly selling drugs to raise money.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Utley|first1=Freda|title=Japan's Gamble In China|date=1938|publisher=Secker and Warburg|pages=34–43|url=http://www.fredautley.com/pdffiles/book21.pdf|accessdate=15 Jul 2015}}</ref>  On February 1, 1938, East Hebei was merged with the [[Provisional Government of the Republic of China (1937–40)|Provisional Government of the Republic of China]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=E. Hopei to Merge|journal=Manchuria Daily News|date=1938|volume=3|page=114|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6BxQAQAAIAAJ&q=east+hopei+autonomous+government+february+1+1938&dq=east+hopei+autonomous+government+february+1+1938&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CB0Q6AEwAGoVChMI18DYpcndxgIVC5mACh0aBg4Q|accessdate=15 Jul 2015}}</ref>

