|[[File:Flag of the Republic of China-Nanjing (Peace, Anti-Communism, National Construction).svg|150px]]
|[[Reformed Government of the Republic of China]], [[Provisional Government of the Republic of China (1937–1940)|Provisional Government of the Republic of China]], and [[Mengjiang]]
|Japan wanted to make [[Wang Jingwei]], the former leader of the [[Provisional Government of the Republic of China (1937–1940)|Provisional Government of China]], the leader of a new puppet government.  But, contrary to what was expected, Wang set up a new [[Nationalism|Nationalist]] government, based on the reunified [[Nationalist Government (China)|Nationalist government]] of 1927.  He requested that the [[Three Principles of the People|Three Principles]] be reinstated, among other things.  The Japanese initially denied this request, viewing the Three Principles as "Western ideas," but eventually accepted, with some exceptions: removal of the requested 5-branch system, and replacing it with a one-party system.  The Nationalist Government retained independence as far as financial matters and economy were concerned, but Japan controlled its politics.<ref>{{cite book|last=Minoru|first=Kitamura|title=The Reluctant Combatant: Japan and the Second Sino-Japanese War|date=2014|publisher=University Press of America|isbn=0761863257|pages=74–75|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QuBhAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA74&dq=Nanjing+Nationalist+Government&hl=en&sa=X&ei=8OiEU5W7B4n68QHnzYH4Dg&ved=0CDkQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q&f=false|author2=Lin Si-Yun }}</ref>  Despite this, the country had no real power, and was mainly used as a propaganda tool.  The country was ended in August 1945.<ref name=pettibone />{{rp|383}}
