|[[File:Flag of the State of Burma (1943-45).svg|150px]]
|[[British rule in Burma|British Burma]]
|Initially, Burma was invaded with the sole objectives of cutting off the [[Burma Road]], a route through which the United States and Great Britain supplied [[Chiang Kai-shek]], and gaining the resources of Burma, mainly rice and gas.  After Japan's successful [[Japanese conquest of Burma|conquest of Burma]], which was completed in May 1942, they began driving the British out, using the [[Burmese Independence Army]].  Once the British were entirely out of Burma, Burma was granted nominal independence, which essentially meant that Burma was called independent, but was really under Japanese control, as part of the [[Greater East Asia Co-Prosperity Sphere]].  After several years, growing dissent in the country led to growing popularity of [[Thakins]] and other anti-government groups like it.  By 1944, they had organized an underground Anti-Fascist Organization, and on 27 March 1945, [[Aung San]] led these and other forces to rise up against the Japanese.  The uprising is remembered as a struggle against "imperialist British" and "fascist Japanese."<ref>{{cite book|last=Seekins|first=Donald M.|title=Historical Dictionary of Burma (Myanmar)|date=2006|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=081086486X|pages=230–231|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zY5F88wiDYYC&pg=PA229&dq=history+of+burma+japanese+occupation&hl=en&sa=X&ei=3C6FU5_4L8y-sQSo3YH4Dg&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>
