|[[File:Flag of the Philippines (1943-1945).svg|150px]]
|[[Commonwealth of the Philippines|Philippines]]
|Following Japan's [[Philippines Campaign (1941–42)|invasion of the Philippines]] in 1941, the Japanese tried to present themselves as liberators from their "colonial repression."  In 1942, a group of influential Filipino politicians tried to negotiate with the Japanese for the creation of a new national government, but this led to nothing more than the creation of the puppet state.  A second factor in the creation of the puppet state was the turning tide of the war: the Japanese believed that the creation of a government that appeared free would boost civilian morale.  On 20 October 1944, US forces began the [[Philippines Campaign (1944–45)|re-invasion of the Philippines]].  The Philippines were effectively  under United States control by July 1945, and a new government set up in August.<ref>{{cite book|last=Marshall Cavendish Corporation|title=World and Its Peoples: Malaysia, Philippines, Singapore, and Brunei|date=2007|publisher=Marshall Cavendish|isbn=0761476423|pages=1188–1189|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=72VwCFtYHCgC&pg=PA1188&dq=Japanese+control+of+philippines&hl=en&sa=X&ei=jzWFU8buKs-YyAS75YGYCQ&ved=0CGcQ6AEwCg#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>
