|[[File:1931 Flag of India.svg|150px]]
|[[British Raj|British India]]
|The Provisional Government of India, sometimes also called the Provisional Government of Azad Hind, was created by Indian nationalists-in-exile in October 1943.<ref name=pettibone /> {{rp|411}}  According to [[Subhas Chandra Bose]] in a proclamation issued on 4 April 1944, the government was formed in [[Syonan-to]] (formerly Singapore) after an invasion of Singapore.  This invasion was wanted "by the unanimous will of the three million Indians in East Asia."  Additionally, he stated that the Provisional Government had but one mission: "to expel the Anglo-American armies from the sacred soil of India by armed force and then to bring about the establishment of a Permanent Government of Azad Hind, in accordance with the will of the Indian people."  He also claimed that "the Indian people will co-operate wholeheartedly with our Ally, the [[Imperial Japanese Army|Nippon Army]], who are giving us unstinted and unconditional assistance in defeating our enemies."  Bose was also "fully convinced <nowiki>[</nowiki>of<nowiki>]</nowiki> Nippon's sincerity towards India."  He also claimed that, given the Government's rapid advance into India, "the circumstances have...rendered it necessary...to borrow from the Nipponese Government the currency...already in its possession and to use that money as a temporary measure."<ref>{{cite book|last=Toye|first=Hugh|title=The Springing Tiger: A Study of the Indian National Army and of Netaji Subhas Chandra Bose|date=1959|publisher=Allied Publishers|isbn=8184243928|pages=186–187|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_ACwkShmNzUC&pg=PA187&dq=Provisional+Government+of+Free+India&hl=en&sa=X&ei=-C-GU-KoM-PLsQSe9ILYBg&ved=0CEIQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>  The Provisional Government was ended shortly after Subhas Rose died in a plane crash on the way to Taiwan, in August 1945.  With his death, much of the [[Indian National Army]] surrendered.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bose|first=Subhas Chandra|title=Subhas Chandra Bose' agenda for Azad Hind: India after independence : selected speeches of Subhas Chandra Bose|date=2000|publisher=Freedom Movement Memorial Committee|location=New Delhi, India|isbn=8190071556|page=164|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=1kSGU91fxKewBLTogeAP&id=cUVuAAAAMAAJ&dq=Azad+hind&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=august+1945|author2=P. S. Ramu }}</ref>  Despite Japan's strong influence in the area, some historians consider the Azad Hind a free and independent government.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Chandra Sarkar|first=Subodh|title=Notable Indian trials
|publisher=M.C. Sarkar; Original from: [[University of Michigan Press]]|year=2008|page=1962|isbn=}}</ref>
