|bgcolor=lightgreen|[[File:Flag of First Slovak Republic 1939-1945.svg|150px]]
|bgcolor=lightgreen|[[Slovakia]], [[Czechoslovakia]]
|bgcolor=lightgreen|Hitler had been having meetings with the Czechoslovakians for years, and had long had plans of making Slovakia a puppet state.  In early March, rumors (planted by Germans) began reaching Slovakian leaders that Germany would give Slovakia economic support if Slovakia gained independence.  German troops began moving in on Slovakia.  On 10 March, diplomatic talks between the Czech Republic and Slovakia had broken down, and Hitler was growing nervous about his plans of a Slovakian puppet state.  He threatened that Slovakia should either declare its independence, or be abandoned.  Later, Germany received a [[telegram]] stating Slovakia's independence, along with a request for German assistance.<ref>{{cite book|last=Crowhurst|first=Patrick|title=Hitler and Czechoslovakia in World War II: Domination and Retaliation|date=2013|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=0857723049|pages=91–93|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uJEAAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA2&dq=slovak+republic+wwii&hl=en&sa=X&ei=jPyIU43ED-HisATAz4GwCw&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>  Shortly after Slovakia's "independence," Hungary (looking to gain land from militarily-weak Slovakia) attacked Slovakia, in what became known as the [[Slovak–Hungarian War]].  During the war, which lasted from 23 March<ref name=axworthy>{{cite book|last=Axworthy|first=Mark W.|title=Axis Slovakia: Hitler's Slavic Wedge, 1938-1945|date=2002|publisher=Europa Books Inc|isbn=1891227416|page=45|url=https://www.amazon.com/Axis-Slovakia-Hitlers-Slavic-1938-1945/dp/1891227416}}</ref> to 4 April 1939, Germany failed to protect Slovakia (in direct violation of their treaty), forcing Slovakia cede 400 square miles (1,036 square kilometers) of land to Hungary.<ref name=axworthy /> {{rp|51–52}}  Despite this, there was at least one plus to German rule: it improved the Czech business sector.<ref name=axworthy />{{rp|111}}{{clarify|Czech, Czechoslovak, or Slovak|date=August 2018}}  Some historians date the end of the Slovak Republic as 11 April 1945, when the [[Slovak National Council (1943-1960)|Slovak National Council]] was instated after the [[Bratislava-Brno Offensive|Soviet invasion]]. Others date it at 8 May 1945, when the Slovak government signed the surrender document.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kirschbaum|first=Stanislav J.|title=Historical Dictionary of Slovakia|date=2013|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=081088030X|page=169|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wzefAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA122&dq=occupied+slovakia&hl=en&sa=X&ei=FSWJU8iVBbegsQSdwYHYAQ&ved=0CEkQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>
