|[[File:Flag of Russian Liberation People's Army.svg|150px]]
|[[Oryol|Orel]], [[Kursk]],  and [[Bryansk]] of the [[Soviet Union]]
|On 22 June 1941, Germany initiated [[Operation Barbarossa]], the Axis invasion of the Soviet Union.  Upon reaching  Orel, Kursk, and Bryansk, the invading forces were greeted by the ardent anti-communist [[Bronislav Kaminski]] and his forces, who were actively fighting the Soviets.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Jan Chodakiewicz|first1=Marek|title=Intermarium: The Land between the Black and Baltic Seas|date=2012|publisher=Transaction Publishers|isbn=1412847869|page=142|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4zSGR3fBfUcC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_atb#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=19 Feb 2015}}</ref>  His force, known as the Russkaya Osvoboditelnaya Narodnaya Armiya, meaning [[S.S. Sturmbrigade R.O.N.A.#Russian National Liberation Army|Russian National Liberation Army]] and abbreviated RONA, was composed of [[Red Army]] deserters, anti-communist [[White movement|white Russian]] collaborators, and a rag-tag group of [[expatriate]]s.<ref name=McNab>{{cite book|last1=McNab|first1=Chris|title=Hitler's Elite: The SS 1939-45|date=2013|publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=147280645X|pages=347–348|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TV7MAQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=20 Feb 2015}}</ref>  RONA's forces were allowed control of the area at some point in November 1941 by [[Rudolf Schmidt]], though it is unclear whether he was acting on his own accord or on another officer's orders.  Though Lokot was initially headed by the founder of RONA, [[Konstantin Voskoboinik]], after Voskoboinik was killed in early 1942, control of the region was transferred to Kaminski.<ref name=Rein>{{cite book|last1=Rein|first1=Leonid|title=The Kings and the Pawns: Collaboration in Byelorussia during World War II|date=2011|publisher=Berghahn Books|isbn=0857450433|pages=287–288|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JCbNmF3iXP0C&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_atb#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=20 Feb 2015}}</ref>  In April 1942, the Lokot region was given limited autonomy.  While in charge, Kaminski's forces rooted out [[Partisan (military)|partisan]] activity with notorious ruthlessness, and became incorporated into the [[SS]] as [[S.S. Sturmbrigade R.O.N.A.]].  In May 1942, after gaining support from [[Alfred Rosenberg]], the region was granted increased autonomy.  By 1943, however, RONA began to suffer many desertions, due to Russia's improved position against Germany, and the Lokot Autonomy was evacuated by August 1943.<ref name=McNab/>{{rp|347}}  
