|bgcolor=lightblue|[[File:Flag of Albania (1943-1944).svg|150px]]
|bgcolor=lightblue|[[Albanian Kingdom (1939–43)|Italian Albania]]
|bgcolor=lightblue|Originally under the control of Italy, the Albanian Kingdom came under the control of Germany after the [[Armistice of Cassibile]] on 8 September 1943.  Living conditions were already very poor in the area due to the Communist leadership of the area, but were worsened due to the wartime occupation conditions.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Goldman|first1=Minton|title=Revolution and Change in Central and Eastern Europe: Political, Economic, and Social Challenges|date=1996|publisher=M.E. Sharpe|isbn=0765639017|pages=53–56|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aLZlX13le_wC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_atb#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref>  Albania was freed from German control on 29 November 1944, when [[Albanian resistance during World War II#Provisional Communist administration|Albanian Communist Partisans]] liberated the last German-controlled city, [[Shkodër]].  As Germany resistance was either fled or was captured or killed, the city grew increasingly desolate.  The Communists began to reassert themselves over Albania, and Shkodër was considered by one Albanian as a "dead city."  The Communists were so aggressive people were afraid to go outdoors.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Pearson|first1=Owen|title=Albania in the Twentieth Century, A History: Volume II: Albania in Occupation and War, 1939-45|date=11 July 2006|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=1845111044|pages=413–416|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P3knunC7z_oC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_atb#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=5 May 2015}}</ref>
|-
|bgcolor=lightblue|<center>1943-09-23</center>
|bgcolor=lightblue|<center>1945-04-25</center>
|bgcolor=lightblue|{{collapsible list
| title = <span style="font-size:90%">{{nowrap|[[Italian Social Republic|Italian Social<br />Republic]]}}</span>
| {{lang-it|Repubblica Sociale Italiana}}
| {{lang-de|Italienische Sozialrepublik}}
