|[[File:Flag of Belarus (1918, 1991-1995).svg|150px]]
|[[Byelorussian Soviet Socialist Republic]], the [[Soviet Union]]
|After [[Operation Barbarossa]], Germany controlled much of the Soviet Union's satellite states, including [[Belarus]].  The [[German occupation of Belarus during World War II|German occupation of Belarus]] began on the same day as Operation Barbarossa (22 June 1941) due to its proximity to the German-Soviet Border.  Initially, the land was included in ''[[Reichskommissariat Ostland]]''.  Early on, much of the state's work was done by either pro-Nazi or anti-communist Belorussian Self-Help battalions, but in April 1943 the chief of German security police in Belarus demanded that all Self-Help groups be disbanded.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Savchenko|first1=Andrew|title=Belarus: A Perpetual Borderland|date=2009|publisher=BRILL|isbn=9004174486|page=133|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lmld75blKCwC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_atb#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=20 Feb 2015}}</ref>  On 21 December 1943, the Belarusian Central Rada (sometimes called the Belarusian Central Council) was formed, and placed under the leadership of [[Radasłaŭ Astroŭski]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Korosteleva|first1=Elena|last2=Lawson|first2=Colin|last3=Marsh|first3=Rosalind|title=Contemporary Belarus: Between Democracy and Dictatorship|date=2003|publisher=Routledge|isbn=1135789487|page=22|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gfeQAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_atb#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=20 Feb 2015}}</ref>  The puppet state was destroyed with the Soviet [[Operation Bagration]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Wilson|first1=Wilson|title=Belarus: The Last European Dictatorship|date=2011|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=0300134355|page=110|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jZJntMQtkSYC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_atb#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=20 Feb 2015}}</ref>
